"Edelweiss" was written by Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein for the 1959 musical, "The Sound of Music." This original recording for the "The Man in the High Castle" title sequence is performed by Jeanette Olsson.

Isa Dick Hackett, daughter of bestselling author Philip K. Dick, is the founder and CEO of Electric Shepherd Productions, LLC. The company is dedicated to the stewardship and adaptation of the Phillip K. Dick library.

Ridley Scott has a long running history of adapting Philip K. Dick's work for the big screen. In 1982, he directed "Blade Runner" adapted from Philip K. Dick's novel, "Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?"

Bestselling author Philip K. Dick published 45 novels and more than 120 short stories. He won numerous awards for his work, including the Hugo Award for Best Novel of 1962 for "The Man in the High Castle."
The theatre's filming location is Seattle, Washington's historic Paramount Theater built in 1928.

The Bald Eagle was chosen as the symbol of the resistance due to its iconic representation of America. With its round head the bald eagle's shape is in stark contrast to the squared off head of the Nazi eagle found atop The Parteiadler. The arrow symbolizes the resistance call to arms.
This 1960's version of Times Square was filmed in a large parking lot located in Seattle, Washington. A majority of the shot, including the buildings and pedestrians were built using CGI.

The neon swastika found in the center of Times Square was inspired by the commercial makeover of Times Square in the 1970's. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Americanization of Nazi iconography is one way the Germans would have institutionalized themselves on US soil.

The most famous German monorail is The Wuppertal Suspension Railway, which was designed by Eugen Langen with the first track opening in 1901. It is still in use today with approximately 85,000 passengers daily. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the monorail system was further developed by the Germans and rolled out across all German territories. In real life, the monorail shown is located in Seattle, WA and was built in 1962.

Rules on what could or could not go in the post during the Nazi's reign in Germany was very strict. Books were handed out in school to teach children about the postal system.

In the world of ""The Man in the High Castle,"" the inevitable control and censorship that would likely have been in place in Nazi Germany would have been adopted by the Greater Nazi Reich, with all mail crossing territories being heavily censored and any ambiguous phrasing blotted out.

'Brown Shirts' is a nickname given to Sturmabteilung (SA), a paramilitary wing of the Nazi party. Fearing he was losing control, in 1934, Hitler ordered the 'Night of the Long Knives' - having many of the heads of the SA assassinated. However, in the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the SA was re-built in the run up to WWII and stayed a vital part of the Nazi power structure after the war.

Germany was the first country to use Closed Circuit TV. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Germans used this new technology extensively across its territories to counteract dissidents and maintain order.

Obergruppenführer - 'Senior Group Leader' is a Nazi Party military rank. It was the highest commissioned SS rank until the rank Oberst-Gruppenführer or Colonel General was created above it, which historically was more of an honorary rank.

The Japanese martial art of Aikido was developed by Morihei Ueshiba and most commonly translates as the 'way of spiritual harmony with the forces of nature'. The word Aikido is made up of three characters of Kanji; Ai - meaning 'to come together', Ki - meaning 'spirit or force of the universe', and Do - meaning 'the way'. Non-violent and non-aggressive, Aikido provides a source of harmony to counteract the disharmonious forces in our world. Primarily made up of circular flowing movements from a relaxed state, it aims to neutralize the aggression without causing harm.

Alexa Davalos ("Juliana") performed four Aikido techniques in this sequence. The first two throws, "heaven and earth" and "breath throw" are from the attack "Ryotetori Tenchinage" which means two hands on two grab. The third throw "Yokomen Uchi" is an angle strike to the head or neck with the end of the hand. The final throw is "Munetsuki Kotegaeshi" which is a straight punch to the middle section with a forearm reverse throw (kotegaeshi).
Each star on the Japanese Pacific States flag represents a state under Japanese occupation.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," 'VA Day' is short for 'Victory in American Day': The official day where American forces surrendered to the Germans and hostilities ceased, paving the way soon after for the establishment of the Greater Nazi Reich. The day is marked each year with nationwide celebrations, comparable to the celebrations of Independence Day.

Theories about Hitler's health problems have been widely debated, with most being hard to prove. However, one theory that is widely speculated is that Hitler may have suffered from Parkinson's disease. It has been suggested that this progressive debilitating disorder affected his personality and decision-making. Newsreel footage might suggest evidence of tremors and postural instability.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Kempeitai keep order in the Japanese occupied Pacific States. They are in charge of intelligence, counter-intelligence and the containment of resistance movements. For this reason, they have replaced ordinary police forces in Japan's overseas territories.
In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," Manga comics arrived with the occupying Japanese forces and quickly became part of popular culture within the Pacific States.
The intent behind creating "The Grasshopper Lies Heavy" film was to choose images that clearly identified the Allied powers took victory over the Axis.

"Popeye the Sailor Man" made his first appearance as an extra in a comic strip called "Thimble Theater," in 1929. At the time of the Great Depression, Popeye's spinach obsession is credited with a 33% rise in the consumption of spinach in the U.S. Popeye joined the U.S. Navy in 1941, appearing in an all-white uniform for the first time in a series to boost the war effort.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," license plates in the Greater Nazi Reich include the slogan: "Arbeit Macht Frei" which translates in English to: "work makes you free." During WWII this phrase of Nazi nationalist ideology could be found at the entrance of various concentration camps. Most famously it hung above the gates of "Auschwitz."

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the totalitarian control of the Greater Nazi Reich becomes difficult to maintain in the area leading to the Neutral Zone, on the very edge of Nazi control in the continent. The defacing of Hitler's image is an indicator of this.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle", the well-known jail on Rikers Island has gone from being a jail to a political prison operated by the SS for the detention of dissidents, political prisoners, spies and disloyal members of the Nazi hierarchy. In our reality, the Gestapo operated such prisons during WWII, one of the most notorious being Montelupich prison in Krakow where 'medieval' torture methods were routinely used as a method of interrogation.

Smith wears the black uniform of an SS Algemeine officer. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," this imposing uniform was brought back to give the feeling that if Hitler won the war, he would have re-issued one of the Nazi party's most iconic looks.
Tattoos have a long tradition in the US Military. What is poignant here is that having been a soldier 'so fierce', as is the nature of war, he now cannot remember what he was fighting for.

'Aktion T4' was the code name for a program of 'mercy killings' of those who the Reich believed, due to physical or mental reasons, were a burden on the state. In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," these policies extend to the elderly and those physically impaired from injury, and is a practice no longer hidden from the population. Society has full knowledge of this law to achieve a pure and productive society.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the German aviation industry utilized the advanced rocket technology they had developed during the war, for military and commercial aircraft, causing it to stride ahead technologically, even against their Japanese rivals.
The scene taking place in "Hirohito Airfield" was shot in the same large parking lot they utilized for the Times Square sequence found earlier in the episode.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," 'Americana' has become a hugely collectible commodity among the Japanese of the Pacific States, who ardently acquire pieces of an idealized and idyllic American history. This has caused a surge in demand for well crafted replicas.

The American interstate highway system was developed in the 1950s, greatly aiding the speed of interstate travel. However, in the world of "The Man in the High Castle," this development wouldn't have happened in the Pacific States due to Japanese occupation. So the bus Juliana travels on uses the older and slower highway system, including Route 66, to navigate its way to the Neutral Zone. The Germans, however, had already developed the autobahn system and would have implemented this across its American territories, greatly aiding the speed of interstate travel. The basis of the U.S. Interstate Highway system was in fact the German autobahns. President Eisenhower, while Military Governor of Germany after World War II, was impressed with the system and the speed with which Germany was able to move its military around the country, so when he became President he proposed the creation of the "Interstate and Defense Highway System" to improve internal transportation within the United States. Eisenhower had personally seen the difficulties of moving military columns across the country while a junior officer.
The design of the payphone umbrella was influenced by both the shape of the German helmet and the modernist movement.

Canon City is a real town that was founded in 1890. While gold was not found there, many precious minerals were discovered in its surrounding towns resulting in the development of rail access. The Royal Gorge Bridge was built in 1929. In 1870, dinosaur bones and fossils were discovered in Canon City. Canon City is also known for having over 10 prisons.

The exterior shots of Canon City were filmed in Roslyn, Washington. Fans of 1990's series "Northern Exposure," might also recognize this area which was turned into the fictitious town of Cicely, Alaska.
The origami unicorn is a nod to Ridley Scott's 1982 film "Blade Runner" in which the character Gaff uses them as his calling card.

In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," the Mark, being significantly stronger than the Yen, is the currency generally adopted in the Neutral Zone. However, the Yen is accepted in certain towns, particularly those close to the Pacific States' border.
In the world of "The Man in the High Castle," time in the Neutral Zone stands still. American war propaganda was never taken down.

The I Ching, known as the Book of Changes in English, is an ancient Chinese spiritual text. Both Confucianism and Taoism, the two main strands of Chinese philosophy, have their roots in the I Ching. Traditionally yarrow sticks, but now sometimes coins, are cast, and the pattern that they produce is known as a "hexagram", the meaning of which is then looked up in the I Ching book. It is a hugely influential classic text, providing guidance and insight, whose interpretations have been debated for centuries. The I Ching is also referred to as "The Oracle".
